Estelle Bennett (July 22, 1941 – February 11, 2009) was an American singer.
Bennett and her sister, Veronica (later known as Ronnie Bennett), grew up in New York City.
Bennett attended George Washington High School in Manhattan where she was valedictorian.
Studious and interested in fashion, she studied at Manhattan's Fashion Institute of Technology.
In 1969, now known as Estal Bond she fronted The Love Chain, an all-women quartet that also featured: Laura Logan, Ann Trip and Cookie Woodson.
She was reported to have had periods of homelessness, during which she would approach strangers in the streets of New York, telling people that she would be singing with the Ronettes in a jazz club.
Bennett died of colon cancer, aged 67, in Englewood, New Jersey.
A week after her death, it was revealed that she had suffered from anorexia nervosa and schizophrenia in the years after the Ronettes' breakup and that she had subsequently been homeless in New York.
She married the group's road manager, Joe Dong, and they had a daughter, Toyin.
